<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="16.[108,1212,1527,1740]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
DIAGNOSIS: Males of this species are distinctive, characterized by greatly lengthened aristalike stylus (figs. 13D, 14A) (2.9 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[475,492,1564,1590]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">×</emphasis>
length of postpedicel), bearing a light, apical flaglike expansion; elongate and flattened palpi; CuA strongly recurved, in line with m-cu; CuA+CuP sharply curved subapically to wing margin. Distinguished from males of 
<taxonomicName box="[906,1078,1639,1665]" class="Insecta" family="Atelestidae" genus="Alavesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longistylata">
<emphasis box="[906,1078,1639,1665]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">A. longistylata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by slightly longer stylus with a light (vs. dark) apical “flag,” broader palpus, longer and narrower wing; cell cua significantly thicker.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
